author: Popescu Nicolae

text: Vlad Èšepes: One of the few great rulers of Romania that brought fear into his enemies through some unique strategies of battle.Â  His most definite mark was that he impaled a huge amount of people with no remorse! Despite what most say, HE DID NOT DO THIS FOR PLEASURE! he was impaling only THIEVES, LIERS and invaders of Wallachia, mostly punishing those that opposed the ways of God. There was no jail time or captures. He executed them on sight, impaling them to set an example.  Because he was so straight with his executions and filled his entire country with impaled bodies terrifying everyone, people started to think that he is evil. Until to the point the story of Dracula started to emerge.  Another reason why he was considered evil was that he impaled even a lot of rich people that tried to betray him. Because of this, those that opposed him tried to make the people hate and fear him by spreading FALSE stories in the hope that his support would diminish and he could be taken down from his throne.  Here are the 2 most infamous strategies that he used to defeat the ottoman empire even if he was greatly outnumbered.  1. He and his men chopped off an entire forest and dressed it as soldiers... When the ottoman soldiers arrived, they retreated frightened of the numbers Vlad armies were posing.  2. 'The night attack'. He and a few men dressed as ottomans went into their enemy camp, starting a riot under the reason "Get up and fight, Romanians have dressed as ottomans and are sabotaging our camp!". This way the ottoman forces slaughtered themselves.  After battles, all of the fallen bodies were impaled to set an example.  Make no mistake, the Ottoman forces could have crushed Romanian forces like bugs. The armies used for their campaign were not to conquer, but to recover the tribute Romanians were supposed to give. This means the numbers of soldiers sent to oppose Vlad was fairly low compared with the entire Ottoman armada!  This is a short and very simplified version of the real Dracula history. The legend is nice, but too far from truth. I like that in this movie Vlad is presented as a DEFENDER, ready to sacrifice all that he has for the sake of his family and people. One way or another this is what he actually did, and i hope this movie will resurrect at least the intentions of Vlad.

text: Vlad began preparations for the reconquest of Wallachia in 1476 with Hungarian support. Vlad's third reign had lasted little more than two months when he was killed in battle against the Turks. The exact date of his death is unknown, presumably 31 October or the end of December 1476, but it is known that he was dead by 10 January 1477. The exact location of his death is also unknown, but it would have been somewhere along the road between Bucharest and Giurgiu. Vlad's head was taken to Constantinople as a trophy

text: Draculaâ€™s standard battlefield death seems less than fitting when compared to the extraordinary life he led. Â One can understand how Bram Stoker was successful in creating a myth from the likes of Vlad Dracula, a man whose life was legendary in its own right. Â Literally hundreds of horrors committed by Dracula were recorded. Â Although history tells the tale of this diabolical Dracula, we are left with Stokerâ€™s prevailing fable of an undead garlic-fearing bat. The only element the two Draculas share in common is their obsession with blood; one loves the gory scene of impalement, while the other is infatuated with biting and sucking his victimsâ€™ necks. I am sure if Bram Stoker somehow presented his mythical Dracula to Vlad Tepes III Dracula, the Voevod would either invite him to a feast, or simply skip the sadistic prelude and have him impaled on the spot.

text: Vlad the Impaler, the son of the dragon (dracula) is morbidly fascinating, but sad. While I understand why he fought against the Ottoman Empire, fighting evil with evil is evil. As for those who say Vlad the Impaler was Christian, that is not true. Like a person who calls himself a vegetarian yet eats beef is not truly a vegetarian, so a person who calls himself a Christian yet does not follow Jesus Christ is not truly a Christian. Jesus Christ commands his followers to love their enemies (Matthew 5:44; Luke 6:27-37). He didn't command them to hurt or kill their enemies. He actually rebuked Peter for using a sword against another person (John 18:10-11) and healed the person whose ear Peter cut (Luke 22:49-51). Jesus Christ allowed the Romans to nail him to the cross. He died once for all, the sinless sacrifice for the sinful. Jesus is the Lamb of God, who takes away the sins of the world. His followers who walked with him didn't kill anybody. After Jesus rose from the dead and showed them, then gave them the Holy Spirit, they told people the Good News (Gospel) of what Jesus Christ said and did! Someday, Jesus Christ will return. That will be a miracle, and that will prove that he has the authority to judge the world. His true followers, however, obey Jesus' commands to love.

text: 1) Sunt roman de 44 de ani, am trait aici mereu pana acum 2) Vlad al 3-lea Tepes ( englezeste poreclit Dracula ori romaneste scris Draculea ) fiul lui Vlad al 2-lea Dracul si nepot al lui Mircea cel Batran, este invaluit in ceatza istoriei noastre. Majoritatea adevarului despre Draculea a fost distrus de catre inamicii lui din razbunare evidenta. Familia Basarab ( stirpea lui Mircea cel Batran ) este trunchiul din care familia Draculestilor s-a desprins. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mircea_the_Elder - grandfather of Dracula http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vlad_II_Dracul - father of Dracula http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vlad_III_the_Impaler - Draculea himself 3) Tatal lui Draculea, a fost cavaler al ordinului Dragonului http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_of_the_Dragon 4) De aceia, Vlad Tepes a fost poreclit â€œfiul draculuiâ€, pentru ca Vlad Dracul purta permanent medalionul ordinului Dragonului la gat. 5) Realmente, pentru a garanta supunerea lui Vlad Dracul, sultanii otomani au pretins pe toti fii lui Vlad al 2-lea, ca â€œmusafiriâ€ ( ostatici princiari ) la curtea imperiala otomana. Desigur, cei doi printi au primit tot ce era mai util simultan cu tot ce era mai nociv din partea otomanilor: atat educatie cat si perversiune. Legenda spune ( si face noima dintr-un anume considerent ) ca otomanii ( cititi Sultanul sau vreunii mari demnitari imperiali ) au supus pe printi la perversiuni sexuale pentru a le amplifica supunerea temeinic verificata. In folclorul roman, se crede ca Vlad Draculea a devenit dusman fanatic otomanilor din aceste cauze, in timp ce fratele sau, Radu cel Frumos, a subcombat constrangerii si s-a islamizat ( pentru a evita violul sau tocmai din cauza violului ). 6) Orice razboinic stie ca lupta incepe din insasi sufletul lui si se extinde prin minte, corp, mediu, natiune, cultura, tot drumul pana la sufletele tuturor dusmanilor sai. 7) Posibil, Vlad Draculea, obsedat de asasinarea tatalui sau de catre rivalii domestici, si rasobsedat de traumele impuse lui si fratelui sau, a folosit ocazia de a cunoaste inamicii sai pana la excelenta: academia militara imperiala si biblioteca imperiala erau deschise celor doi printi. A invatat tot ce a putut chiar sub nasurile otomanilor, le-a invatat strategiile, tacticile, limbile, puterile. Tot ce avea nevoie pentru a ii combate pana la disperare si chiar mai mult. 8) Curand, Vlad Draculea a fost investit, DE CATRE OTOMANI, conducator al Valahiei, in partea de sud a ceia ce este azi, tara mea, Romania. Otomanii au inteles prea tarziu uriasa gafa pe care au facut-o. Vlad a reorganizat urgent natiunea sa decazuta. A marginalizat abuzivii si nemernicii, a exterminat parazitii si mai ales a oripilat toti tradatorii si dezertorii. In ultimii 24 de ani am contemplat declinul treptat al natiunii mele, ascensiunea sistematica a tradatorilor, abuzivilor, demagogilor, mincinosilor si asemenea indivizi. Pot spune sincer ca Vlad Draculea nu a pierdut timp pentru a regenera tara lui intr-o natiune militanta. In prezent posibilii nostri prieteni ne compatimesc, rivalii nostri ne ridiculizeaza, dusmanii nostri de tot felul ne dispretuiesc si umilesc cu fiecare ocazie. Tanjim cumplit dupa un lider eficient ca Vlad, pana in punctul in care am imbratisa un monstru. 9) Pentru a se imputernicii, Dracula si-a sacrificat extensiv umanitatea: a exercitat masiv TEROAREA, ATROCITATEA, URA EXTREMA pentru a lupta cu dusmanii bastinasi sau straini. 10) Desigur, razboiul economic a fost cel mai greu: negustorii brasoveni, si nu numai, erau rivali religiosi, politici si etnici. Pretindeau tot mai mult, si cu cat primeau tot mai mult cu atat se saturau mai putin. Cautau subjugarea economica a Valahiei, apoi metoda cu metoda, pana la completa subjugare sufleteasca si religioasa. Pestele mare inghite pestele mic, mereu. 11) Infuriat de abuzul brasovenilor, Dracula i-a reprimat extrem de crud. I-a arestat pe toti: barbati, femei, copii, tineri si batrani, sanatosi si bolnavi. Traditia spune ca i-a internat intr-un lagar de exterminare prin munca, la fel ca nazistii, si i-a supus exterminarii laborioase, pentru a construii fortareata de la Poienari. Toti foarte putinii supravietuitori la sfarsitul constructiei au fost aruncati de pe stanci, pentru a coplesii toti dusmanii trecuti, prezenti si viitori ai lui Vlad si ai Valahiei. 12) Razboiul real este precedat de razboiul psihologic, iar Dracula a invatat asta pe pielea lui, apoi a practicat asta asupra dusmanilor fara crutare. 13) Pentru a il distruge, toti inamicii sai s-au raliat intr-un pact nescris prezentandu-l drept un MONSTRU mult mai mare decat cel in care a fost Dracula nevoit sa sa transforme. El chiar a devenit un monstru in constiinta lui, dar inamicii sai au confiscat asta de la el si l-au agravat intr-un monstru inca mai rau. Inamicii sai aveau nevoie sa pozeze in vanatori de demoni si atunci au avut nevoie sa-l satanizeze complet. 14) Concluzie: Draculea a FOST NEVOIT sa sacrifice hoarde de ticalosi pentru a proteja putinii nevinovati pe care i-a mai gasit in natiunea lui. Ingrozitoarea lui â€œcruciadaâ€ a fost scurtata de intriga, tradare, siretenie. A luptat contra unor sanse cumplit de defavorabile si a oferit neamului foloase extreme daca evaluezi instrumentele pe care le-a avut la dispozitie. Valahia lui Dracula si Romania mea necesita conducatori eficienti, mantuitori implacabili, chirurgi biologici-mentali-sufletesti daca mai e sa ajunga macar pana la respect, daca nu pana la glorie. Simtim permanent ca suntem pe lista de sacrificiu, ca proprii lideri ne vand in paguba la orice ocazie, ca riscam soarta pieilor rosii din America de nord: impingerea in rezervatii catre o agonie lenta, finalizata in exterminare si disparitie istorica. 15) Soarta noastra pare foarte sumbra: tinerii nostrii dispera si degenereaza, batranii nostri se resemenaza si decad. Solicitam indivizi de eficienta lui Vlad Tepes, pentru a ne recupera si pentru a ajunge la capatul timpului. Voi nu ati simtii la fel ? 16) Dumnezeu sa-i impace sufletul in nemarginita Lui mila. Ne-a lasat un exemplu si macar speranta ca va mai apare un alt lider ca el care sa ne ridice la valoarea noastra completa.

text: First the English version of a romanian's comment ====== 1) I am a 44 old romanian, lived here all my life 2) Vlad III the Impaler ( english nicknamed Dracula or romanian written Draculea ) son of Vlad II Dracul, and grandson of Mircea the Elder ( Mircea cel Batran ) is a individual shrouded into the mist of our history. Very much of the truth about Draculea was removed by his enemies, revenge being obvious. The family of Basarab ( Mirceaâ€™s lineage ) was the main branch out of wich the family of Draculesti split. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mircea_the_Elder - grandfather of Draculea http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vlad_II_Dracul - father of Draculea http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vlad_III_the_Impaler - Draculea himself 3) Yes, Draculaâ€™s father was a knight of the order of the Dragon http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_of_the_Dragon 4) As such, Vlad was nicknamed â€œfiul Draculuiâ€ ( the son of the Devil / Dracul ), â€œfiul lui Draculeaâ€ because Vlad Dracul always wore the orderâ€™s medallion on his neck. 5) Indeed, to secure Vladâ€™s II Dracul loyalty, the sultans of the Otoman Empire asked for all his sons, as â€œguestsâ€ ( read royal hostages ) to the Otoman imperial court. Of course, the two brothers got the best AND the worse of the court: both education and perversion. The legend says ( and it makes some sense from the psychological term ) that the otomans ( read - the Sultan or some very high officials ), subjected both young men to perverse sexual rites, to assess theyr submision. In our romanian folklore, the say is that while Vlad Dracula became fanatical enemy of the otomans for this reason, Radu the Handsome ( Radu cel Frumos ) submitted under the pressure and converted to Islam ( either to avoid the rape or because of it ). 6) Any fighter knows that fight starts into his very soul, and extends trough his mind, body, enviroment, nation, culture, all the way to every of his enemies. 7) Plausible, Vlad Draculea, haunted by his fatherâ€™s death at the hands of his domestic rivals, and overhaunted by the psychological traumas he and his brother were subjected to, took the oportunity to study his enemies to the point of excelence: the otoman military academy was open to the two princes, the imperial library as well. He learned all he could, right under the nose of the otomans. He knew theyr strategy, tactics, languages, power. All he ever needed to fight them into despair, and some extra. 8) Soon Vlad Dracula was crowned, BY THE OTOMANS, leader of Wallachia ( Valahia ), into the southern part of what is today my country, Romania. The otomans realised too late theyr huuuge blunder. Vlad wasted NO TIME to organise his falled nation. He marginalised the abusers and the unworthy, exterminate the parasites and most of all horrified all defectors and traitors. For the last 24 years I contemplated the gradual decline of my nation, the relentless rise of traitors, abusers, demagogues, liars and such. I can honestly say that Vlad Dracula wasted no time to redeem his country to fighting condition. Curently, our would be friends pitty us, our rivals look down to us, our enemies of any nature despise us and humiliate us each time. We dearly long for a leader eficient like him, to the point that we would embrace a monster. 9) To empower himself Dracula sacrificed his humanity extensively: he used brute TERROR, ATROCITY, EXTREME HATRED to wage his fight abroad or at home. 10) Of course the economical war was the hardest: the merchants of Brasov and many others, were of foreign faith and politics and ethnicity. They asked more and more: the more they received the MUCH more they asked, until they started to plunder directly. They sought to subjugate Wallachia economicaly, then means after means, until full psychological and religious subjugation. The big fish eats the small fish, always. 11) Enraged by their abuse Vlad Dracula punished them extremely cruel. He arrested them all, men, women, children, young and old, healthy and ill alike. Traditions says that he used them into a labour camp, much like the nazis, and subjected them to extermination regimen, to build the castle of Poienari. All the very few survivors at the end of the construction were thrown from the edge of the mountain to certain death bellow, to further seed terror into the souls of all his enemies. 12) The real war is always preceeded by psychological war, and Dracula learned that on his skin, and practiced it on his enemies without sparing. 13) To destroy him, all his enemies banded themselves into an unwritten pact: depict him as a worse MONSTER than he needed to become. He became a monster into his own conscience, but they took that from his soul and forged him into a far worse monster. His enemies needed to pose as devil hunters, so they needed to satanise him fully. 14) Conclusion: Dracula HAD TO sacrifice huuuge lots of villains to save the few inocents he found into his nations. His horrible â€œcrusadeâ€ was cut short by intrigue, betrayal, cunning. He fought against overwhelming odds and delivered extreme use to my nation considering the means at his disposal. Draculaâ€™s Wallachia back then, and my Romania right now, need eficient rullers, unwavering saviours, biological, mental and psychological surgeons to rise again at least to respect, if not to glory. We feel every moment that we are on the list of the sacrificed, that our own leaders trade us on every turn, that we risk the fate of the red skins of north America: pushed into reservations to slowly agonize to extinction, and out of history. 15) Our fate seems very grim, out young grow desperate and corupt more and more, our elders grow resigned and decadent. We need people of Draculaâ€™s efficiency, to recover and live to see the end of time. Would you not fell the same if you were to be us ? 16) May his soul be put to rest by God in his infinite mercy. He left us the example of his eficiency and the hope that some day another leader like him will raise us to our merits

Reading his story, is like joining the dots that makes a clear and powerful figure. What is very surprising is that though he gave, the Vatican the ability to spread Christianity around the globe. The Church not only gave him the grand title, or not of the devil/dragon, to spread fear in the Islamic world. They destroyed him utterly; after a successful lifetime battle with the Ottoman Caliphate. He stopped this unstoppable force, after the fall of the greatest city in the Christian world, Constantinople/Istanbul. The Church/Vatican, gave Prince Vlad money, and some soldiers. Anyway he not only beat the Ottoman Empire on his own. But 'they never continued to venture into Christian lands anymore'. In history Islam begin to weaken in all aspects, and ventured into it's Dark Ages. Only after Prince Vlad won, then Europe soon realized that they could expand, in 'all forms'. No one really sees this, because Vlad was made into a monster, which the Church did easily. All they had to do was to tell people his was a real monster, but he was not a real monster. text: Historic Dracula (Vlad) in medieval Wallachia was a merciless and a brave man! His deeds had been an effort which was to have painful repercussions even today. For example:  "his impaling exploits [were] seized upon by Ivan the Terrible in Russia. Vlad had shown himself to be a hero of the Orthodox faith and a model of the harsh, autocratic ruler. As such he was taken to justify Ivanâ€™s supposed divine right to tyranny and sadism." (Leatherdale, Dracula: The Novel and the Legend, 216)  The story that he dipped his bread into the blood of those impaled before him had been a clerical propaganda which shows the extent to which Vlad terrorized the imagination of the Medieval Europe. However at the end, Vladâ€™s position eventually weakened as the Ottomans gripped the control of Wallachia. Radu the beautiful, as we all know, defeated Vlad in a landslide with a support from Ottomans. In Romania, after 19th century, as a "Conditio sine qua non", he served to nationalist purposes. In the imagination of Turkish historiography (in the past), however, he remained a magnet for the evil. As to the film, it is fantasy amalgamating historic Vlad to Stoker's Dracula.

text: Due to the mixed critical reviews, I was afraid this trailer was another Clash of the Titans situation. In which a handful of epic scenes are strung together in a well made trailer to make the movie look far better and entirely different then it really is.  Fortunately this was not the case at all. The movie takes a new look at the legend of Dracula and truly earns its name sake of being Untold. Dracula is portrayed in an entirely different fashion with a loveable story which brings a new shine to an old and somewhat dull legacy that has been sorely overused. The story takes into account both the historical aspects of Vlad and the fictitious facts of Dracula to combine them into a very real feeling story, which pays homage to both fields.  The movie suffers some several hiccups in the plot and scene set up, which show that this is indeed the director's film debut. Combat at times can get a bit blurry, but its hard to keep the camera on track of a guy who has acquired the powers of Satan. ItÂ brings several new and creative elements into the scenes and plots, which allow for several surprises with the clever use of things that just have not been done before. It takes quite a bit of tact to make a full length movie surrounding a guy who can instant kill his enemies all at once.  Although it holds several flaws, Dracula Untold has a great deal of charm and intricacy that makes it a great thing to waste an hour and a half on watching. I definitely will be adding it to my collection when it comes out for sale.

text: Vlad the Dracula was not Romanian per se, since the Romanian nationality formed much later. He was a decedent of House Of Basarab, who were ethnically Pechenegs (Turkic speaking nation) of christian faith settled around northern shores of Black Sea. According to the Ottoman Law all lands of empire belongs to Sultan, that contradicts to the General Turkic Law that Beys (in which case House of Basarab) have authority to rule over their possessions. So Vlad the Dracula was contesting his authority to rule over his lands. P.S. Most of his army were mercenaries that is why he got broke at the end.

text: In fact, Vlad III never mastered Transylvania, but the territory granted to them is the region of Wallachia, Romania. He was the son of Vlad II, who gave up the power of the Ottoman Empire at the time of Murad II, Mehmed II's father. Mehmed II and Dracula is indeed hostile, but Mehmed never die at the hands of Dracula, the opposite happened, Dracula is defeated in the feud with Mehmed II.Â   Illustration of Vlad III Dracul Dracula versus actual existing in HollywoodÂ  "Dracul-ae" the Romanian language designation for the noble Order of the Dragon (Romanian; Draco = Dragon), and the suffix "-ae" means "son of". As for the "Order of the Dragon" itself is one of the group of knights were prepared by the King Sigismund Holy Roman Empire as a special warrior in the crusadeÂ  The name itself refers to Vlad Dracula III "Tepes", son of Vlad II voivode (governor) of Wallachia, Romania. At the time of his father Vlad II, Wallachia ruled by the Ottoman Empire, and as a guarantee of loyalty, Vlad III (Dracula) and then sent to schooled in the Ottoman EmpireÂ  Dracula / Vlad III and educated in Yeniseri unity, a special forces military Turkish Empire with his brother Radu Cel Frumos. That is where they learn best in military units of its time. Age Dracula was still young, 13 years alone, the difference is only one year older than Mehmed II, the son of Murad II, Sultan of Turkey at the time.Â  However, although still young, has been sworn in Dracula Dragon Order that was formed to fight against the Muslims, and so that's what his intention. Therefore he hates Mehmed and Islam, although his brother Radu Cel Frumos be Muslim and commander Yeniseri Mehmed trust, in turn, took office when the Sultan of Turkey.Â  When his father Vlad III Dracul, Vlad II was killed and the coup in 1447 by John Hunyad of Hungary, the Ottoman Empire and helped liberate from the clutches of John Hunyad Wallachia. After that Sultan Murad II, Mehmed II's father, then asked the father of Vlad III to replace lead in Wallachia.Â  Despite allegations Sultan Murad II, this is the long-awaited opportunity Vlad III Dracul, who from the outset had hated her father because she wants to submit to the Muslims. Armed with Arabic, Turkish and military knowledge in Yeniseri, Dracula disguised as part of the Muslims in every Muslim fortresses and forts finish Islam in Romania from within.Â  Post-1453 Sultan Mehmed II, who holds the Al-Fatih conquered Constantinople since, sent some emissaries to make sure everything is fine in the year 1459. Wallachia Vlad III Dracul Mercilessly kill the messengers of the Sultanate of Turkey who came to collect the jizya (taxes for the disbelievers) are supposed to be paid every year. Looking for trouble, Vlad III killed these messengers by nailing their turbans to his head. On the pretext that the messenger acted brash, no honor by not want to take off his turban, and just wanted to open his turban before God.Â  On hearing this Sultan Mehmed II of Wallachia and respond to problems in particular. In 1461 Sultan Mehmed II ordered his commander Hamza Bey brought 1,000 troops to capture Dracula and restore stability in the region of Wallachia, and the fate of the 1,000 troops it ended tragically.Â  Dracula using infiltration capability with what he learned in Yeniseri, he really understands the tactics and strategies to fight the Muslims, then the effective movements, Dracula then beat and slaughtered 1,000 Muslim troops. Dracula impaled (stab with wood from the anus to penetrate into the esophagus) is 1,000 troops, to be a human corpse forest. Hamza Bey, the commander of this army, stationed in the jungle corpse and placed in the highest wood as a symbol.Â  Vlad III Dracul since it got the title of "Tepes" or "The Impaler" - "The Impaler", cruelty known and recognized worldwideÂ  Found this, Sultan Mehmed II and commissioned Radu Cel Frumos, the younger brother of Vlad III Dracula to lead 90,000 troops to stop Dracula. Need to stop wolf wolf, Mehmed understand that the right person because Radu Romania plateau could only be understood by the originalÂ   Cel Frumos Radu (Radu the Handsome), the younger brother of Vlad III DraculÂ  In contrast to his brother Vlad III Dracula, his brother Radu Cel Frumos (The Handsome), embraced Islam and became a Muslim and leader of special forces Yeniseri. Radu led 90,000 through the woods and hilly ground to attack his brother Romanian Dracula who survived in the fort 'Poenari' propertyÂ   Catatea Poenari, Vlad III Dracula FortressÂ  This battle was not easy, considering Cetatea Poenari (Poenari Fortress), the land is very steep and difficult to penetrate. Finally Radu attack at its peak in 1462 occurred the night Poenari Fortress known "Atacul de noapte" - "The Night Attack"Â  Radu Cel Frumos be replaced Dracula of Wallachia leader after defeat. Dracula is fighting a losing battle to save yourself and run to ask for protection on Hunyad John King of Hungary. Dracula spend the rest of his life under the rule of his father's killer, John Hunyad are also rivals Sultan Mehmed the other, before finally Dracula died in 1478 also slashed the sword of Ottoman troops.Â  But Dracula remains eternal legacy to the world, unmatched cruelty that he demonstrated, and savagery without limits. Until now recognize as a hero Romanian state in the crusade, and statues scattered in Romania. For Muslims, Dracula is a symbol of the cruelty of the enemies of humanity, human awl, and sucking blood. But this time the concept of Dracula, Vampires, made â€‹â€‹and wrapped up with a nice lure Muslims and forget the original faceÂ  Hollywood is clever propaganda by twisting history, and make the Muslim Turkish Empire as violent, barbaric, cruel and inhumane. Whereas in fact quite the contrary, Muslim forces are benevolent forces, demonstrating chivalry and basic indigo values â€‹â€‹such as courage, honesty, compassion and forgiving.

text: Great movie. Give it a chance people, it is Hollywood, but it is still Dracula, vampires, epic battles and decent acting. For the haters though, and those that like to comment about Romania, Vlad the hero, and how the Turks took his head..... Vlad Tepes the third, was not a vampire, he was a cruel ruler, forged by necessity. He was raised by the Turks, and for a reason I can't "fathom" he disliked them a lot. To the point that he wanted to "Impale" them all. Driving a fat pointy stick through the bottom and ehm well, you get the point. Such perversions are not that common, can you only imagine through what he went through to develop such.... peculiarities? Â His father was betrayed by those closer to him, his allies turned on him.... He was One against everyone. Can't say I don't feel bad for him being so lonely, and despite all that he experienced he turned to the only thing he could do, he used fear as his weapon, fear was his only true ally. A patriot and a military genius, he was able to take on far superior forces and defeat them. He did so much with so little, he didn't have a big empire or any Sultan backing him up, all he could expect was a dagger in the back. As a human being i am not condoning to his cruel actions, but I think i can understand him a bit. And i can't help but wonder, if he had a proper army and aid from the West....He could have defeated the Ottomans, perhaps even throwing them back out of the Balkans. Well, what the heck? If the "Noble" Christians couldn't do it, then he, a monster could. Enjoy the movie.

text: The Real Untold Story of How the Muslims killed the Dracula Â  â€œHe who controls the present controls the past.â€ [1] Many will be aware of the new Hollywood film which has been recently released entitled: â€˜Dracula Untoldâ€™. It might not be well known that, supernatural powers aside, the tale of Dracula is actually based on a real person. Unfortunately however, this film is such a fictitious remake that it speaks volumes about the rise of Islamophobia as well as it does about the Westâ€™s attempts to seek to rewrite history by glamorising mass murders whilst peddling the fear of the â€˜Muslim invadersâ€™. What follows is a summarised account of the real, well-known history of Dracula. Vlad Dracula was a three-time Voivode of Wallachia (modern day Romania), ruling mainly from 1456 to 1462, the period of the emergent Uthmani Khilafah, the Ottoman Caliphate, and its conquest of the Balkans. His father, Vlad II Dracul, was a member of the Order of the Dragon, which was founded to protect Christianity in Eastern Europe and was fashioned after the military orders of the Crusades requiring initiates to defend the Cross and fight the so-called â€œenemies of Christianityâ€, in particular the Muslim Ottoman Caliphate. Childhood There was a time, when much of what is modern Bulgaria, Romania, Ukraine, Belarus, the Balkans, the Crimea and almost all of southern Russia was ruled by Muslims. This was once part of the Muslim heartland of IslÄm, the Ottomon Empire and produced many great leaders and scholars. Today of course, the only majority Muslim community found in mainland Europe is in Bosnia, Kosovo and al-Baniya, Albania. The Christian communities in Hungary and Wallachia wanted to fight against the Ottomans, however they were very weak and there was much disunity amongst them. In 1436, Vlad II Dracul ascended to the throne in Wallacia only to be dethroned by those loyal to the King in Hungary, JÃ¡nos Hunyadi. Vlad II sought the help of the Ottoman Muslims who in turn sought payment of the Jizâ€™yah, a tax which non-Muslims pay to a Muslim ruler in return for their protection from outside nations. As part of this deal, Sultan Murad II asked that Vlad II send two of his four sons to Istanbul to be educated. Vlad II agreed and so he sent his two sons and he in turn was ascended to the throne again in Wallachia by the Ottomans. The two sons who travelled back with the Muslims to Edirne were Vlad Dracula and his younger brother, Radu. Vlad is the one who we have now come to know as Dracula because the word Dracula means â€˜son of Draculâ€™ which was the name of his father. The word â€˜Draculaâ€™ has of course since taken on a different meaning, being synonymous with a devilish evil, and we will see why this is. Whilst under the tutelage of the Ottoman Muslims, the boys were provided with education including that of Islamic texts. Radu became Muslim and was a close friend with the young boy of the Sultan Murad II, Muá¸¥ammad (Mehmet II). Vlad however was rebellious and is recorded to have developed a well-known hatred for Muslims even though he too studied the Qurâ€™Än, spoke Arabic, Persian, Turkish and of course Wallachian (Romanian). In 1447 the King of Hungary attacked Wallachia and killed Vlad Dracula and Raduâ€™s father and brothers. Given that Vladâ€™s father had paid the Jizâ€™yah, the Muslims defended them against the Hungarians and they installed Vlad Dracula in power. In the meantime, Radu at the age of 22 became a leading MujÄhid (one who strives in the path of AllÄh) within the Ottoman court and commanded the Janissaries (the foreign contingent of the army). He was sent by his good friend Muá¸¥ammad, who by this stage had become the Sultan at the age of 19, to subdue various rebellions such as that in Anatolia. Perhaps more importantly, he participated alongside Sultan Muá¸¥ammad in the Ottomon siege which eventually led to the fall of Constantinople in 1453. Constantinople was the capital city for the Roman Byzantine Empire. Napoleon was quoted as once saying, â€œIf the Earth were a single state, Constantinople would be its capitalâ€ [2]. As for Sultan Muá¸¥ammad, he was from here on forever to be known as Muá¸¥ammad FÄtiá¸¥ (Muá¸¥ammad the Conqueror), and his new city was from here on forever to be referred to as Islambul, meaning the â€œCity of IslÄmâ€. It should be noted that it was only during the secularisation process of Ataturk where it took on the name of â€˜Istanbulâ€™ which has no relevant meaning. Incidentally, there are coins in the British Museum from 1730 where the name of the city, Islambul is clearly imprinted [3]. By conquering Constantinople, Sultan Muá¸¥ammad FÄtiá¸¥ had also fulfilled the blessed words of the Messenger of AllÄh (sallAllÄhu â€˜alayhi wasallam) who said concerning this event: â€œVerily, Constantinople shall be conquered. Its commander shall be the best commander ever, and his army shall be the best army ever.â€ [4] Crusades With the fall of Constantinople, Pope Pius II called for crusade in 1459 against the Ottoman Muslims, at the Congress of Mantua. In this crusade, the main role was to be played by Matthias Corvinus, son of JÃ¡nos Hunyadi, the King of Hungary. To this effect, Matthias Corvinus received from the Pope 40,000 golden coins, an amount that was thought to be enough to gather an army of 12,000 men and purchase 10 warships. In this context, Vlad Dracula allied himself with Matthias Corvinus, whose family it should be remembered killed his family, with the hope of keeping the Ottomans out of the country. The Declaration of War Later that year, Sultan Muá¸¥ammad FÄtiá¸¥ sent emissaries to Vlad in Wallachia to urge him to pay a delayed jizâ€™yah which Vlad Dracula had put off paying. Unknown to the Ottomans, Vlad Dracula had already allied himself with the Hungarians and joined the Popeâ€™s call for a Crusade against them. Vlad Dracula met with the emissaries and said to them, â€œIf you want to step inside of my port, you have to take off your turban and bow.â€ The Muslims responded that they would not remove their turban and â€œwe only bow to AllÄhâ€. So Vlad once again demanded, â€œTake it offâ€ and again they refused. Vlad Dracula then told someone to come with some very big nails and hammers and he said, â€œIf they refuse to remove it for me then they will never remove it again.â€ And he commanded that their turbans be nailed into their heads. Of course, this resulted in them being killed â€“ this act was a declaration of war against the Muslims which Vlad Dracula had been spoiling for. Sultan Muá¸¥ammad FÄtiá¸¥ sent the Bey of Nicopolis, Hamza Pasha to eliminate Vlad Dracula. Vlad Dracula however planned an ambush. Hamza Pasha, the Bey of Nicopolis, brought with him 10,000 cavalry and when passing through a narrow pass north of Giurgiu, Vlad Dracula launched a surprise attack. The Christians had the Muslims surrounded and defeated and almost all of them were caught and impaled, with Hamza Pasha impaled on the highest stake to show his rank. Impalement was Vlad Draculaâ€™s preferred method of torture and execution and it was this which makes him stand out in being remembered as absolutely evil and barbaric. Impalement is the penetration of an organism by an object such as a stake, pole, spear or hook, by complete (or partial) perforation of the body, often the central body mass. What they would do is get a very long stick, make sharp one end and insert it through a personâ€™s back passage, driving it through their body until it came out of their mouth. Often, the victims would be alive and this is how they would be killed. Then they would put this stick into the ground and impale others, putting them next to each other. Massacres In the winter of 1462, Vlad Dracula crossed the Danube and devastated the entire Bulgarian land in the area between Serbia and the Black Sea. Disguising himself as Turkish, utilising the fluent Turkish he had learned whilst under the care of the Muslims, he infiltrated and destroyed Ottoman camps. In a letter to Corvinus of Hungary, he wrote: â€œI have killed peasant men and women, old and youngâ€¦ We killed 23,884 Turks (Muslims) without counting those whom we burned in homes or the Turks whose heads were cut by our soldiersâ€¦ Thus, your highness, you must know that I have completely broken any peace with him (Sultan Muá¸¥ammad FÄtiá¸¥).â€ Vlad Draculaâ€™s attack was celebrated by the then western Christendom; the Saxon cities of Transylvania, the Italian states and the Pope. A Venetian envoy, upon hearing about the news at the court of Corvinus, expressed great joy and said that the whole of Christianity should celebrate Vladâ€™s successful campaign. The Genoese from Caffa also thanked him. In response to this, Sultan Muá¸¥ammad FÄtiá¸¥ raised an army of around 60,000 troops and 30,000 irregulars, and in spring of 1462 headed towards Wallachia. This army was under the Sultanâ€™s commandership and in its ranks was his friend and brave MujÄhid, Radu. Vlad Dracula was unable to stop the Ottomans from crossing the Danube on June 4, 1462 and on entering Wallachia, they found that on one of the very long roads leading to the capital of this area were 20,000 Muslims impaled along the sides of these roads. Imagine this, we suffer today no doubt but incidents of such brute are very rare indeed. You can imagine how Sultan Muá¸¥ammad FÄtiá¸¥ felt to see even one Muslim killed which was too much to bare, but to mutilate their bodies after this was something, which was beyond acceptable. Vlad Dracula constantly organised small attacks and ambushes on the Muslims and adopted what we would call today â€˜Guerrilla warfareâ€™. Pausing for a moment and thinking of the current state of the Muslim world, it is clear that it is now the Muslims who usually adopt guerrilla tactics in view of their weakness and inferior military might whereas Muslims were in the time of Muá¸¥ammad FÄtiá¸¥, the superpower of the day. The End Game After some time, Radu, who remained faithful to IslÄm and the Sultan and spent his entire life on the frontlines of JihÄd and battle in protection of the frontiers of the Ottoman Empire, was charged with the responsibility of pursuing his brother and thus showing the world that in IslÄm, brotherhood in faith is given priority over blood relations where they have an enmity towards the faith. Vlad Dracula was running out of funds and returned to Hungary to seek help from Corvinus, who instead of helping Vlad Dracula, imprisoned him as he was seen as a liability even for the Christians. In his absence, Radu defeated the remnants of Vlad Draculaâ€™s army and became the ruler in Wallachia and he ruled from 1463-1473 when he died at the age of 40. Meanwhile, Vlad Dracula was released from prison and he returned to Wallachia once again and retook power in 1476 with Hungarian support. He immediately assembled an army and invaded Bosnia, slaughtering its Muslim population and impaling 8,000 on stakes in a forest of human bodies. Vlad Dracula had arisen from the darkness with the objective of eliminating IslÄm from the Balkans once and for all and installing Christianity. Sultan Muá¸¥ammad FÄtiá¸¥ invaded Wallachia and faced the forces of Vlad in Bucharest, Romania. Vladâ€™s army was overrun in a blitz and all were killed, including Vlad himself. His head was removed from his body and was taken back to Istanbul. They impaled his head and put it at the gates of Islambul where it stood for about 2 â€“ 3 months to send a clear message to others. â€œIf you want to be like this man, then dare wage war against us.â€ Points to note This was the demise of Dracula and again as Muslims, most of us will not even know about this. How many people even know that Dracula was a real man? It is very important that we do not allow distractions such as this new filmâ€™s fictitious rewriting of history to shape our understanding of what really happened. The film is truly shocking in its attempt to rewrite history, in portraying a man who was truly barbaric and brute in nature, as a brave man and a hero. They seek to show that his war with the Muslims started because he was seeking to protect his children, which of course is far from the truth; this was a man who did not care about family. What is more insulting and offensive is that by portraying Vlad as a hero, they are portraying his enemies, the Muslims as being barbaric and thereby also insulting the great man whom the Messenger of AllÄh (sallAllÄhu â€˜alayhi wasallam) had spoken about, Sultan Muá¸¥ammad FÄtiá¸¥. Many Muslims had tried before Muá¸¥ammad FÄtiá¸¥ to be the best commander ever as prophesied in the Hadith by attempting to conquer Constantinople for over eight hundred years, making ten attempts. Among them were some of the greatest men whose names shine as bright stars including â€˜Uthman b. â€˜Affan (radiyAllÄhuâ€˜anhu), Muâ€™awiyah b. AbÅ« SufyÄn (radiyAllÄhuâ€˜anhu), AbÅ« AyyÅ«b al-Ansari (radiyAllÄhuâ€˜anhu) who was martyred and buried there, SulaymÄn b. Ê¿Abd al-MÄlik, Harun al-RashÄ«d, and many Muslim commanders from the age of the Umayyad Caliphate, â€˜Abbasid Caliphate and also the â€˜UthmÄni Caliphate. This was a man whom when asked about his capabilities and how he managed the conquest, replied: â€œI have two traits: 1) a heart as hard as a rock that does not rest until I achieve what I want; (2) an eye that cries out of fear of AllÄh jalla waâ€™ala. So how could I not achieve victory?â€ It was to defend his honour, raá¸¥imahu AllÄhu (may AllÄhâ€™s mercy be upon him), and that of the Muslims who were martyred at the hands of the Dracula, may AllÄh grant them all Jannah (Paradise), that caused me to write this article. Unfortunately, we find certain desperate, lowly movements in the West through the many weapons in their armoury, including the make-believe propaganda tool that is Hollywood, demeaning this noble champion of IslÄm whilst upholding a bloodthirsty savage who committed many atrocities against humanity and in doing so, they legitimise his crimes and not a word of condemnation will you find being uttered from their lips. It would be inconceivable that a film be made to depict Hitler as a hero but yet the Muslim community is hated so blindly by some in todayâ€™s society that not many will even see this issue in that context. As a New Statesman article recently put it: â€œThe vilification of IslÄm has reached such heights that when the Sultan Muá¸¥ammad FÄtiá¸¥ is cast opposite historyâ€™s bloodiest psycho-tyrant, itâ€™s Dracula who emerges as the tragic hero [5].â€ What is apparent from the film is that it recreates evil as good and good as evil. It reaffirms the narrative which is prevalent in current times and the strategy deployed against Muslims. Aa famous statement from Malcolm X (raá¸¥imahu AllÄhu) comes to mind when he said: â€œIf you are not careful, the newspapers will have you hating the people who are oppressed, and loving the people who are doing the oppressing.â€ So there you have it. You will often hear the saying that garlic kills a â€˜Draculaâ€™ or a silver bullet or a wooden stake through the heart â€“ of course none of these killed Dracula. Indeed it was the Muslims who killed the Dracula. Let this serve as a reminder to the many bloodthirsty Draculas we have in our midst today, that if anyone wants to follow his way, they too will face the same wrath from the Muslims until justice is restored for all of humanity. text: Technically then, this does not seem to be about Vladislav Dracula. This is about Vladislav Dracul, his father. Seeing as It was Vlad Dracula and Radu who were taken away as wards for the Sultan. That is where Dracula comes from, the 'a' signifies him as the son of Vlad Dracul, not Vlad Dracul himself. Just calling him Vladislav Dracul II was too mainstream.  Also, people saying that this is stupid because he wasn't a hero or because Vampires are not heroes, from the looks of things he is not a hero in this. In fact, more than from the looks of things, it specifically states it in the narration. And seeing as this is, rather, about his father rather than The Impaler himself, I do not see why it matters whether you consider Vlad Tepes a hero or not, although, if anything he was an anti-hero, setting impalement to be the punishment for every crime, no matter now small, may not seem "just" but it certainly fixed the crime-rate and made the justice system simpler. And the 20,000 Turkish prisoners-of-war he impaled were invaders after all, it was in defence of his country, even if impaling them all to send a message was a bit extreme and even if he did still loose in the end. And by a bit extreme, I mean very extreme, that is just how Christianity rolled back in the day, the Muslims were historically a lot more tolerant of Christians than visa-versa.

Vlad's brother, Radu the Handsome, died many years earlier and had been replaced on the Wallachian throne by another Turkish candidate, Prince Basarab the Elder, a member of the DÄƒneÅŸti clan. When Vlad's army arrived, Prince Basarab's army fled, some to the Turks, others in the mountains. After placing Vlad on the throne, Stephen BÃ¡thory and his forces returned to Transylvania, leaving Vlad in a very weak position. Vlad had little time to get support before a large Turkish army entered Wallachia to put Prince Basarab back on the throne. Vlad had to meet the Turks with the small forces at his disposal, which were made up of fewer than four thousand men. Vlad III declared his third reign in 26 November 1476, where it had lasted little more than two months and thereafter he was killed. According to profs. McNally & Florescu, Vlad Dracula was killed in battle.[12]  There are five variants of Vlad's death. Some sources[who?] say he was killed while having sex with one of the Turks surrounded by the bodies of his loyal Moldavian bodyguards. Others say he was killed by disloyal Wallachian boyars also in the war against the Turks, or during a hunt. Lastly, other reports claim that Vlad was accidentally killed by one of his own men. The exact date of Vlad's death is unknown, presumably the end of December 1476, but it is known that he was dead by 10 January 1477. The exact location of his death is also unknown, but it would have been somewhere along the road between Bucharest and Giurgiu.[citation needed]  According to Bonfinius (Antonio Bonfini) and a Turkish chronicler,[13]Vlad was decapitated by the Turks as a trophy, and his head was sent to Constantinople (now Istanbul) preserved in honey. After, the head was displayed on a stake as proof that he was dead.  Burial[edit] Vlad's body was buried unceremoniously by his rival, Basarab Laiota, possibly at Comana, a monastery founded by Vlad in 1461.[14] The Comana monastery was demolished and rebuilt from scratch in 1589.[15] FAKÄ°NG Ä°DÄ°OTS

text: The truth is people don't really know much about Vlad the Impaler. He wasn't exactly the person he is portrayed to be. He didn't kill for pleasure, he killed because he had to.  You see, Romania has always been a small country surrounded by big empires, like the Russian, the Ottoman and the Austro-Hungarian. We were a very rich country in resources and had very good land for agriculture and that's why all of these empires had made our people's lives miserable. They were making our people slaves, they were taking tributes from us more than we could afford and if we wanted a better life, they just invaded our country to take them by force.Â  In the battles, they had armies at least 3-4 times bigger than ours and they had trained soldiers meanwhile, we had mostly simple peasants. This is why people like Vlad the Impaler, Stephen the Great or Mircea the Elder are the greatest characters in our history. Because, unlike other cowards, they stood for their country (by the way, back then Romania was divided in 3 regions). Stephen the Great even won 46 out of 48 battles against the Turks. Can you believe what a big achievement this is? With armies full of peasants, they beat the Turks' armies of hundreds of thousand of trained soldiers.  About Vlad the Impaler, yes, he had very cruel strategies, but in the end, this was the only way to protect his country. It is said that during his reign, you could have left a bag full of gold in the middle of the street and the next day, you would find it in the exact same place, because every little crime was punished with death by impale. His tactics managed to keep order in the country and scare the Turks armies who were coming after us because every single one of them caught alive had a long and painful death. Say what you want about his tactics but he withstood and defeated the big Ottoman Empire with them.  And I don't really understand why are the Turks so proud about controlling Romania in the past. You had millions of soldiers. We had a few ten housands and still some of our great leaders defeated you several times. And because of your big ambitions, your empire fell in the end and you became a normal country just like us.Â   PS: Just search on google those people I mentioned earlier and you will see many more interesting things.

text: In 1462 III. When Vlad's armies were defeated, Eflak was again linked to the Ottoman State. Vlad escaped to Erdel, a principality attached to Hungary, seeking help from Hungarian king Matthias Corvinus. However,  Hungary, which defined the new administration of the Ottoman Empire in  Wallachia, did not accept the request for assistance. Vlad Matthias was arrested by Corvinus in 1462 and brought to Budin. First imprisoned, Vlad later established good relations with the king and his family. In 1474 the period of exile ended. Since then, he has made plans to recapture Wallachia. In 1476 he returned to Wallachia with his cousin Stefan Cel Mare (Great Stefan) and was announced on voyage. In the same year, he was defeated again by Ottoman armies with 300 soldiers. His captive soldiers were seated in the piles. Killed III. In order to prove that Vlad's head was killed, He was sent to Mehmet. The story that Vlad was a vampire spread in Germany, Hungary and Russia. Despite this, the Romanian people continued to see him as a hero.
